children.subject: I took 161 and got a lot of exposure to crypto, would 194 be repetitive at all?
Also have a look at math 136 or philos 140b.

If you liked the sections on NP-completeness/reductions/halting problem in 70/170, and want to learn more about what computers fundamentally can/cannot do efficiently (or at all), I recommend 172 in the spring.

If you liked modular arithmetic/RSA from 70, 194-34 (cryptography) is another good option. The class builds up provably secure encryption/authentication schemes from simple first principles and cryptographic primitives.
174 might be a lot more appealing to you than 126

history.content:
Hi, I realized this summer that I'm really interested in theoretical CS -- I loved CS 70/170, and found the systems-focused classes a bit more dull. What should I take?

I'll be taking 189 in the spring, and plan on taking EECS 127 + CS 186 in the fall. I'm wary of taking EECS 126 since I've heard the workload is tough (and I'll be pursuing research during that semester).

I'd like to take Stat 281A eventually, but I'm worried about the prereqs. Any suggestions for similar classes on Bayesian statistics or more advanced mathematical modeling?
history.subject: Really interested in theoretical side of CS
